          "body": "The chapter opens with a rhetorical question that demolishes every attempt to leverage religious infrastructure as leverage over God: *where is a house you could build for Me? And where is a place that I may rest?* (66:1). The question echoes Solomon's prayer at the temple's dedication (1 Kings 8:27: 'the heaven and the highest heaven cannot contain You'), but Isaiah sharpens it into polemic. The false worshipers of verse 3 believe their sacrificial acts secure God's favor; the opening verses destroy that assumption at its foundation. God's hand made *all these things* (66:2a) — the materials of any temple are already His; the ritual cannot add to what He already owns. The pivot in verse 2b is therefore all the more stunning: this God who fills the cosmos looks to 'the one who is humble and contrite of spirit, and who trembles at My word.' Three Hebrew adjectives — *ani* (afflicted, lowly), *nakheh* (smitten, contrite), *chared* (trembling) — define the person who catches the divine gaze. Not the sacrificer with the largest ox, not the architect of the grandest temple, but the person whose spirit is broken before God's word. The same constellation appears in Isaiah 57:15 and 61:1 and surfaces in Jesus's Beatitudes (Matthew 5:3-4). The chapter that will end with fire for the rebels begins with the Lord's tender gaze at the crushed."
